00:01:56.100 --> 00:02:00.120 position:56%
What is life like with two writers
and two small children in the house?

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:04.340
I mean what's an average
day for you?

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:06.960
&gt;&gt; Well it involves a lot
of coffee early in the game.

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:09.670
&gt;&gt; I saw that quote in the Guardian
about espresso drinks being all

00:02:09.670 --> 00:02:11.260
that stand between you
and creative disaster.

00:02:11.260 --> 00:02:12.560
&gt;&gt; And I wasn't kidding.

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:14.100
It really is true.

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:17.570
I mean we get woken up
earlier than we would like

00:02:17.570 --> 00:02:21.300
and in a less dignified
fashion than we would like.

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:26.400
And yeah -- and the first few
hours of the normal business

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:31.250
of the preschool run and
getting everybody settled

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:35.620
and then finally we both
have a coffee in our hands

00:02:35.620 --> 00:02:37.770
and the ability to
escape to our desks.

00:02:37.770 --> 00:02:39.070
It means that --

00:02:39.070 --> 00:02:40.370
&gt;&gt; Katie Kitamura: We stagger up
to our desks and sit down and --

00:02:40.370 --> 00:02:41.670
&gt;&gt; [laughing] I know I'm
an editor, not a writer,

00:02:41.670 --> 00:02:45.500
but I also rely intensely on
coffee to get through the morning.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:50.700
What did you not expect about
being a two writer household?

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:54.710
What came as a complete
surprise to you?

00:02:54.710 --> 00:02:57.660
&gt;&gt; I mean I think -- I mean
often we're asked about,

00:02:57.660 --> 00:03:01.190
you know whether it's competitive
being in the two writer kind of --

00:03:01.190 --> 00:03:03.630
especially because our books
came out within three weeks

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:05.420
of each other earlier this year.

00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:07.260
And I just don't -- I mean
I don't know about you --

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:09.770
I just don't feel that
[laughing] at all.

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:12.180
I mean I think we're
very different writers.

00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:14.780
I mean I don't know.

00:03:14.780 --> 00:03:16.080
I feel like we're both trying

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:17.380
to move the project
forward in some way.

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:22.060
So that's absolutely not an
element of the relationship at all.

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:23.670
I mean I think there's --

00:03:23.670 --> 00:03:25.490
&gt;&gt; I mean when we first got
together we used to live

00:03:25.490 --> 00:03:31.630 position:56%
in a little studio apartment and,
you know there was a room with a bed

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:34.690
and two desks facing
in opposite directions

00:03:34.690 --> 00:03:38.330
and we both wrote novels in there.

00:03:38.330 --> 00:03:41.830
And I think we discovered
that if we could do that

00:03:41.830 --> 00:03:45.930
and essentially be together
more or less 24 hours a day

00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:50.470
and were still happy to
be in each other's company

00:03:50.470 --> 00:03:52.060
that was an indication

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:54.480
that we should probably
get married and reproduce.

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:55.780
[laughter] So --

00:03:55.780 --> 00:03:57.080
&gt;&gt; I mean I think it's --

00:03:57.080 --> 00:03:59.270
&gt;&gt; We went ahead and did that
and then added more obstacles

00:03:59.270 --> 00:04:01.410
in the shape of, you
know little people.

00:04:01.410 --> 00:04:02.710
[laughter]

00:04:02.710 --> 00:04:04.320
&gt;&gt; But I think it's also
the fact that the practice

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:07.700
of writing is actually much more
flexible than you think it is.

00:04:07.700 --> 00:04:09.310
I think -- you know I
don't know about you,

00:04:09.310 --> 00:04:12.280
but when I started writing
I would have my rituals

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:14.360
and I thought I needed to write
first thing in the morning kind

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:17.710
of between seven and 11 when
I was fresh and all that goes

00:04:17.710 --> 00:04:21.280
out the window certainly
once you have children,

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:24.510
but even before then I think, you
know when you're living together

00:04:24.510 --> 00:04:25.810
and you're trying to
make work together.

00:04:25.810 --> 00:04:29.450
And I think the kind of
capaciousness of a relationship

00:04:29.450 --> 00:04:33.910 position:56%
and of a fiction writing practice
is -- took me by surprise certainly.

00:04:33.910 --> 00:04:36.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; That is something actually -- you
anticipated a question I was going

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:38.640
to ask because I mean there
have been whole books dedicated

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:39.940
to writers' routines.

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:41.520
I mean people are almost
religious about it.

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:43.940
You know I get up, I
have a cup of hot water,

00:04:43.940 --> 00:04:47.560
I have to write 5,000 words
before two p.m. and then --

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:49.770
you know I'm pulling that
off the top of my head,

00:04:49.770 --> 00:04:51.070
but it seems like that's kind

00:04:51.070 --> 00:04:53.130
of incompatible [laughing]
with a family life.

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:54.430
&gt;&gt; It really is.

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:57.790
I mean I used to be -- I mean I
call it throat clearing really.

00:04:57.790 --> 00:05:00.100
I mean it used to take
me kind of hours of --

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.450
the sort of equivalent
of aligning up my pencils

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:07.150
on the desk before I could actually
feel psychologically capable

00:05:07.150 --> 00:05:10.120
of sitting down, but now I know

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:13.630
that I have really a relatively
short time and I have to be able

00:05:13.630 --> 00:05:21.770
to kind of access the zone
very quickly and efficiently.

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:24.360
I mean I have little
techniques to get myself

00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:26.070
into my headspace kind of quickly.

00:05:26.070 --> 00:05:29.870
I mean I -- you don't like to
write with music on but I do.

00:05:29.870 --> 00:05:34.940
So I wear noise cancelling
headphones and make my own sort

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:39.200
of space in -- amidst the
chaos of the household

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:45.070
and I now am quite good at sort of
stripping away the outside world

00:05:45.070 --> 00:05:49.040
within 10 minutes or
so and getting into it.

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:51.180
&gt;&gt; It's almost like deadline
pressure except you have no idea

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:53.120
when the deadline is
actually going to be.

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:54.420
[laughing]

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:55.720
&gt;&gt; It's an existential deadline.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:57.020
[laughter]

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:58.320
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:05:58.320 --> 00:05:59.620
&gt;&gt; I mean it's --

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:00.920
&gt;&gt; [laughing] Oh God!

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:02.220
I mean that actually sounds

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:03.520
like it might be productive
for a writing practice.

00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:04.820
[laughing]

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:06.120
&gt;&gt; I mean it was very good for me
in a way to have some constraints

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:07.530
when I was single and
affectively could spend all day --

00:06:07.530 --> 00:06:11.270
I mean pretending that I
was in touch with the muse.

00:06:11.270 --> 00:06:13.990
You know I could waste
huge amounts of time

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:17.990
and I find these days I do
much more in much less time

00:06:17.990 --> 00:06:19.290
because of that pressure.

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:24.440 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I mean I think it was taking me
maybe two years or a little bit more

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:28.600
to write a book before we had
children and then after my --

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:30.730
our son was born I
think I wrote my --

00:06:30.730 --> 00:06:32.660
this book, "A Separation"
in about nine months.

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:34.790
It's just -- there was some
element that you just really had

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:37.060
to sit down and get to it.

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:38.540
And I mean it's -- I mean

00:06:38.540 --> 00:06:40.350
when you're promoting a book
you're often asked to kind

00:06:40.350 --> 00:06:41.720
of describe your working space

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:44.920
and our working space is
complete chaos for both of us.

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:47.600
&gt;&gt; Yeah, it's not the sort
of aesthetic situation

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:51.040
where the magazine is going to
do the sort of lifestyle spread.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:52.340
[laughter]

00:06:52.340 --> 00:06:53.640
&gt;&gt; No.

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:54.940
&gt;&gt; About it.

00:06:54.940 --> 00:06:56.240 position:56%
Unless there's a magazine that wants
kind of, you know kid underwear

00:06:56.240 --> 00:06:58.090
and half eaten sandwiches.

00:06:58.090 --> 00:07:00.750
&gt;&gt; Yeah, that's -- but you
kind of write out of that chaos

00:07:00.750 --> 00:07:04.380
and that has started to
feel quite good in some way.

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:07.890
&gt;&gt; [laughing] How does living
together as writers kind of --

00:07:07.890 --> 00:07:09.420
do you play off each other?

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:10.740
Do you edit each other?

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:12.630
Are you bouncing ideas
of each other?

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:14.570 position:56%
Or is it very like, "I have my lane.

00:07:14.570 --> 00:07:15.870
You have your lane."

00:07:15.870 --> 00:07:17.280
&gt;&gt; Stay out of my lane.

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:18.580
[laughing] No.

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:20.610
&gt;&gt; We've found what's
really -- I mean because --

00:07:20.610 --> 00:07:28.250
Katie's my best reader and
my first reader and I --

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:31.350
in a way you don't want
to waste that read.

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:35.510
You don't want to be kind of
tugging on the sleeve every day

00:07:35.510 --> 00:07:36.810
and saying, "Is it good?"

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:38.110
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:07:38.110 --> 00:07:39.410
&gt;&gt; "Am I good?"

00:07:39.410 --> 00:07:40.710
&gt;&gt; Mom! Mom!

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:42.010
&gt;&gt; And you won't -- and that
I think would definitely --

00:07:42.010 --> 00:07:44.490
you know if we were both
requiring a certain sort

00:07:44.490 --> 00:07:49.340
of emotional reassurance
from each other

00:07:49.340 --> 00:07:51.460
that might get things
too tangled up.

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:55.630
So what we do is we don't
really speak about our projects

00:07:55.630 --> 00:07:57.400
for a very long period of time.

00:07:57.400 --> 00:07:58.850
I mean you go off to your room.

00:07:58.850 --> 00:08:00.150
I go off to my room.

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:01.450
And we do our thing.

00:08:01.450 --> 00:08:02.750
We meet for lunch.

00:08:02.750 --> 00:08:04.050
We talk about other things.

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:06.800
We -- you know we -- maybe in
general terms about our work

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:10.570
but I haven't read a word of the
novel that you've been working

00:08:10.570 --> 00:08:16.540
on for the last year
and a half and same.

00:08:16.540 --> 00:08:22.880
So I mean we'll get to the point
of full drafts and hand it over

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:27.910
and actually then -- I mean I
think people get very tangled

00:08:27.910 --> 00:08:33.990
up with what they need from their
partner and what I need from Katie

00:08:33.990 --> 00:08:35.290
when I give her a draft

00:08:35.290 --> 00:08:40.080
of my writing is an extremely
hard edged, professional read.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:43.030
I don't need her to
tell me I'm okay.

00:08:43.030 --> 00:08:44.330
[laughter]

00:08:44.330 --> 00:08:48.210
&gt;&gt; I mean I think it's also
kind of an exciting moment

00:08:48.210 --> 00:08:50.470
because we do live and
work in the same space

00:08:50.470 --> 00:08:53.540
and I mean we do spend
24 hours a day together.

00:08:53.540 --> 00:08:54.840
&gt;&gt; A lot of time together.

00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:57.520
&gt;&gt; We spend a lot of time together
and so it's quite exciting in a way

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:00.150
to kind of appreciate your partner

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:02.740
for this incredible book
they've written rather than --

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:04.470
&gt;&gt; Yeah, that's their
privacy to be reminded

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:08.220
that there is this thing going on
that you had no idea about at all.

00:09:08.220 --> 00:09:10.060
&gt;&gt; You still feel like; I
don't actually know everything

00:09:10.060 --> 00:09:13.320
that is inside his brain and
it's nice to see your partner not

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:16.360
in the register of "I love him
because he changes the diapers

00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:17.660
and he unloaded the dishwasher,"

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:19.800
but it's like this
incredible imagination

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:21.180
and this is what has been going on.

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:24.090
So it's actually -- it's
nice we're together.

00:09:24.090 --> 00:09:25.520
&gt;&gt; It's kind of romantic.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:26.910
&gt;&gt; [laughing] It's even romantic.

00:09:26.910 --> 00:09:28.410
&gt;&gt; You know but we spend
all this time together

00:09:28.410 --> 00:09:29.960
but there is still
some kind of amount

00:09:29.960 --> 00:09:32.080
of privacy between us I think.

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:34.680
&gt;&gt; It's interesting that you say
that because one of the things --

00:09:34.680 --> 00:09:37.810
I think we talked about it a little
over email and I definitely noticed

00:09:37.810 --> 00:09:40.510
when reading your books
-- is that there are --

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:43.570
there's a little bit of overlap
I think in some of the themes.

