Was that like a -- was that
something you thought about

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:05.890
or noticed or did it just bleed
back and forth between you?

00:10:05.890 --> 00:10:13.750 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I think we -- yeah, I mean we
have meshed into a kind of shared --

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:15.050
&gt;&gt; Set of concerns?

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:20.260
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I think that's true and
our tastes in what we like to read

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:23.830
and what we're thinking about
kind of overlap considerably.

00:10:23.830 --> 00:10:26.470 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I mean I would -- I think I would
have said our books were completely

00:10:26.470 --> 00:10:30.010
different, but then as they've
been out in the world --

00:10:30.010 --> 00:10:32.010
I mean I think we did
a reading together once

00:10:32.010 --> 00:10:34.690
and we both read things
that were about --

00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:37.470
specifically about local
performance and specifically

00:10:37.470 --> 00:10:39.950
about something uncanny in this
book, performance, [agreeing noise]

00:10:39.950 --> 00:10:42.400
and specifically even
about grief in some level.

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:44.680
And so then you realize
that actually we are sitting

00:10:44.680 --> 00:10:46.530
around thinking about the same
things, but they have come

00:10:46.530 --> 00:10:48.450
out in totally different ways

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:51.480
because no two people will write
even the exact same story the

00:10:51.480 --> 00:10:52.780
same way.

00:10:52.780 --> 00:10:54.420
&gt;&gt; I mean stylistically
we're very different writers.

00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:55.720
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:10:55.720 --> 00:10:57.020
&gt;&gt; That's true.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:58.320
When I was reading the books
that was sort of the first thing

00:10:58.320 --> 00:10:59.660
