00:33:39.460 --> 00:33:43.680
I'm interested, since Petra
brought up your children,

00:33:43.680 --> 00:33:48.030
you are both from immigrant
families.

00:33:48.030 --> 00:33:50.740
You're -- Hari I know
you're British/Asian,

00:33:50.740 --> 00:33:54.390
now you live in America
-- Japanese American.

00:33:54.390 --> 00:33:56.510
What is the culture that you --

00:33:56.510 --> 00:33:58.580
how do you bring up your
children in that milieu?

00:33:58.580 --> 00:34:03.550
And how does that affect the
language that they'll use?

00:34:03.550 --> 00:34:06.090
I particularly think of
British-English because I'm

00:34:06.090 --> 00:34:08.960
from there too and my children
still give me a hard time

00:34:08.960 --> 00:34:11.390
about some of the words that I use.

00:34:11.390 --> 00:34:14.640
But it's a very interesting
mix and I think as writers,

00:34:14.640 --> 00:34:17.240
obviously you think
about words all the time.

00:34:17.240 --> 00:34:21.330
I'm curious as to how you think
about the words your children --

00:34:21.330 --> 00:34:24.980
with such an interesting
background from both of you.

00:34:24.980 --> 00:34:29.630
&gt;&gt; We are -- I mean we've -- both
of us have had to kind of break

00:34:29.630 --> 00:34:32.700
from our parents' first language.

00:34:32.700 --> 00:34:34.600
I mean I wasn't brought
up speaking Hindi.

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:36.760 position:56%
My mom's English and my dad's Indian

00:34:36.760 --> 00:34:41.480
and they took the decision
not to speak Hindi to me.

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:44.440
Or my father's decision not to
speak Hindi to me and my brother

00:34:44.440 --> 00:34:48.980
in the home in order not to
sort of alienate my mother.

00:34:48.980 --> 00:34:52.960
And that means that
I don't have that --

00:34:52.960 --> 00:34:59.510 position:56%
I mean when I go to see my family in
India and they would naturally speak

00:34:59.510 --> 00:35:04.410
in a kind of -- in a flowing in
and out of Hindi and English.

00:35:04.410 --> 00:35:07.510
They just skew towards English
when I need to be included

00:35:07.510 --> 00:35:09.170
and then skew away again.

00:35:09.170 --> 00:35:12.370
[laughter] And you -- I
mean your brother is fluent

00:35:12.370 --> 00:35:13.670
in Japanese, your older brother.

00:35:13.670 --> 00:35:15.210
But you were born over here and --

00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:16.520
&gt;&gt; My brother's fluent in Japanese.

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:17.820
He was born in Japan.

00:35:17.820 --> 00:35:20.570
I was brought up in California
and it was a bilingual household

00:35:20.570 --> 00:35:23.280
until I was five and then
I went to kindergarten

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:25.440
and my English was behind.

00:35:25.440 --> 00:35:26.910
And so my parents were advised

00:35:26.910 --> 00:35:29.600
to stop speaking Japanese
to me in the home.

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:32.880
Which is now -- you would
never say that to a family.

00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:35.820
So my Japanese is poor at best.

00:35:35.820 --> 00:35:39.680
And it's something I think
I really, deeply regret.

00:35:39.680 --> 00:35:42.770
And when I look at our
children, who should maybe --

00:35:42.770 --> 00:35:44.070
&gt;&gt; Be trilingual.

00:35:44.070 --> 00:35:45.370
&gt;&gt; Should be [laughing]
trilingual but will be,

00:35:45.370 --> 00:35:49.040
you know very monolingual
unless we do something about it.

00:35:49.040 --> 00:35:51.610
So I think now as they're
getting older I do kind of think.

00:35:51.610 --> 00:35:54.630
&gt;&gt; I mean what they do
have is a sense of culture

00:35:54.630 --> 00:35:58.770
as something multiple and something
that's constructed within a family.

00:35:58.770 --> 00:36:00.820
I mean I think that's something.

00:36:00.820 --> 00:36:03.840
I mean they have this --
the grandparents in London

00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:07.400 position:56%
and there's a family in North India,
there's the family in California.

00:36:07.400 --> 00:36:09.630
There's family in Japan.

00:36:09.630 --> 00:36:11.840 position:56%
And so they know that -- in a way --

00:36:11.840 --> 00:36:13.780
that we've taken this
decision to be together

00:36:13.780 --> 00:36:17.870 position:56%
and to make our little family, which
is not shaped like other families.

00:36:17.870 --> 00:36:19.850
So I think they understand
that each -- in that way --

00:36:19.850 --> 00:36:22.070
that each family does do that work.

00:36:22.070 --> 00:36:24.860
Because even if you're all from
the same place and you don't move

00:36:24.860 --> 00:36:29.780
around you are still making
a culture as a family unit.

00:36:29.780 --> 00:36:32.780
So I mean how that will
play out we don't know,

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:35.620 position:56%
but I mean we have these
conversations about how to keep them

00:36:35.620 --> 00:36:38.960
in touch with aspects of
our cultures that we want

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:43.570
to keep hold of, much the same
as all immigrants do have.

00:36:43.570 --> 00:36:45.560
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I'm interested in
ultimately how it's going

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:47.800
to affect the English that --

00:36:47.800 --> 00:36:49.100
&gt;&gt; You mean it's --

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:50.400
&gt;&gt; English?

00:36:50.400 --> 00:36:51.700
Yeah, I mean they have some --

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:53.750
&gt;&gt; Our son's definitely got a
funny little English accent going

00:36:53.750 --> 00:36:55.520
on in there in the middle of his --

00:36:55.520 --> 00:36:56.820
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:36:56.820 --> 00:36:58.120
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Which I can't --

00:36:58.120 --> 00:37:00.960
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I think the influence
of school is so strong

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:05.110
that once they're really school
age I think it tends to fall away.

00:37:05.110 --> 00:37:10.490
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I mean that's what we will
see that once he's got a peer group

00:37:10.490 --> 00:37:14.790
in grade school then that
will presumably be his primary

00:37:14.790 --> 00:37:17.060
cultural influence.

00:37:17.060 --> 00:37:18.360
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:19.660
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:37:19.660 --> 00:37:20.960
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:37:20.960 --> 00:37:22.260
We have time for one more question

00:37:22.260 --> 00:37:26.040
if anybody wants to
step up to the mic.

00:37:26.040 --> 00:37:28.420
Anybody out there?

00:37:28.420 --> 00:37:29.720
[laughter] Gosh, you
guys are so quiet.

00:37:29.720 --> 00:37:31.020
Here comes somebody.

00:37:31.020 --> 00:37:32.320
Thank you.

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:33.620
[laughing]

00:37:33.620 --> 00:37:34.920
&gt;&gt; Hi. Thank you.

00:37:34.920 --> 00:37:36.220
That was really helpful.

00:37:36.220 --> 00:37:40.070
I was wondering, you said that
there was a set of shared concerns

00:37:40.070 --> 00:37:43.140
that you have even though obviously
your work is really different

00:37:43.140 --> 00:37:45.670
aesthetically and tonally,
stylistically.

00:37:45.670 --> 00:37:53.260
And maybe you could talk about what
those set of shared concerns are.

00:37:53.260 --> 00:37:54.560
&gt;&gt; [laughter] What a question!

00:37:54.560 --> 00:37:55.860
&gt;&gt; Or not.

00:37:55.860 --> 00:37:57.160
&gt;&gt; What do we share?

00:37:57.160 --> 00:37:59.320
&gt;&gt; What else could you do
with this five minutes?

00:37:59.320 --> 00:38:01.680 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I mean I think both of us have --

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:05.050
for biographical reasons
that we've outlined here --

00:38:05.050 --> 00:38:08.410
we've got a sense of
not being in the center

00:38:08.410 --> 00:38:09.940
of the worlds that we occupy.

00:38:09.940 --> 00:38:14.040
I mean I have habitually
written narrators and characters

00:38:14.040 --> 00:38:18.840
who are somehow at an
angle to the situation

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:20.580
that they find themselves in.

00:38:20.580 --> 00:38:26.860 position:56%
And that perspective I think we both
share because we have moved around

00:38:26.860 --> 00:38:32.160
and we have had similar sets
of experiences in some way,

00:38:32.160 --> 00:38:33.520
even though -- I mean our --

00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:37.410
the actual places we grew up
in have been more different.

00:38:37.410 --> 00:38:38.710
&gt;&gt; I mean I feel --

00:38:38.710 --> 00:38:40.010
&gt;&gt; And so that -- yeah, go on.

00:38:40.010 --> 00:38:42.160
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I think maybe there's
an interest in trying to work

00:38:42.160 --> 00:38:46.940
out how to play with narrative.

00:38:46.940 --> 00:38:49.890
So I mean I think as we
mentioned a little bit,

00:38:49.890 --> 00:38:55.550
my book kind of avoids this strong
finish I guess you might say.

00:38:55.550 --> 00:38:59.010
And then Hari -- I mean this
book is -- it almost is very,

00:38:59.010 --> 00:39:01.290
very propulsive and it's
almost the opposite direction,

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:05.120 position:56%
but I think it's the same concern
in a funny way about narrative drive

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:07.110
and how you subvert
a narrative drive

00:39:07.110 --> 00:39:08.550
or you exploit a narrative drive.

00:39:08.550 --> 00:39:10.480
And certainly in "Gods without
Men" you were interested

00:39:10.480 --> 00:39:13.310
in doing something, which was --
which is a book that is really told

00:39:13.310 --> 00:39:17.520
in shards and it has many, many
narratives about how you play

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:20.540
around with this idea of a linear
-- of a kind of more conventional,

00:39:20.540 --> 00:39:22.440
linear narrative and you do
something different with it.

00:39:22.440 --> 00:39:25.840
So I think we also have --
they kind of express themselves

00:39:25.840 --> 00:39:27.800
in very different ways
but I think we both,

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:32.670
for example would have an interest
in form and narrative maybe.

00:39:32.670 --> 00:39:35.040 position:56%
Do we have any -- we must have more.

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:36.690
[laughter] We must have more.

00:39:36.690 --> 00:39:38.090
&gt;&gt; List of shared stuff.

00:39:38.090 --> 00:39:39.390
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:39:39.390 --> 00:39:40.690
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:39:40.690 --> 00:39:41.990
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:39:41.990 --> 00:39:44.890
&gt;&gt; Well I just have one
more quick question for --

00:39:44.890 --> 00:39:46.190
we have like two minutes left.

00:39:46.190 --> 00:39:47.950
Do you have any advice?

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:50.910
Any pearls of wisdom for
people trying to make a go

00:39:50.910 --> 00:39:53.940
of a two writer household?

00:39:53.940 --> 00:39:57.490
&gt;&gt; I would say don't mistake
the bedroom for the desk.

00:39:57.490 --> 00:39:58.790
[laughter]

00:39:58.790 --> 00:40:01.200
&gt;&gt; Sage advice.

00:40:01.200 --> 00:40:06.700
&gt;&gt; The -- [laughing] and by that I
sort of mean you know you want love

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:12.150
and support and you want to be
absolutely secure with your partner

00:40:12.150 --> 00:40:16.370
and you want a reader and a
critic to tell you the truth

00:40:16.370 --> 00:40:19.890
about your work and those are two
very separate sorts of things.

00:40:19.890 --> 00:40:24.650
And don't -- you know don't
mistake somebody saying,

00:40:24.650 --> 00:40:27.340
"That's not working"
for "I don't love you."

00:40:27.340 --> 00:40:29.930
[laughing]

00:40:29.930 --> 00:40:36.170
&gt;&gt; I think it's really important
to be willing to continue

00:40:36.170 --> 00:40:40.100
to give your partner the space
to step away from the family

00:40:40.100 --> 00:40:43.620
to do the work, which sometimes
they do need to be able to do.

00:40:43.620 --> 00:40:46.830
And I think you have to
respect that and it's hard.

00:40:46.830 --> 00:40:50.990 position:56%
It's hard to kind of say, "Yes, take
those two weeks to go away and work

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:53.190
on your book and I'll be here
[laughing] with the kids," but --

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:54.780
and we've both done
that for each other.

00:40:54.780 --> 00:40:57.360
But it's really important
and it's important --

00:40:57.360 --> 00:41:00.500
I mean you know what it takes to
write a book and you know when some

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:03.130
of it -- and you also have
to be sensitive sometimes --

00:41:03.130 --> 00:41:06.930 position:56%
you know one or the other of us will
need that time more than the other

00:41:06.930 --> 00:41:09.750
and then you need to give
it to that person and trust

00:41:09.750 --> 00:41:12.290
that it'll come full circle
and when you're in that place

00:41:12.290 --> 00:41:14.870
and you're writing that you
will also be given that time.

00:41:14.870 --> 00:41:19.310
I mean I think it's dangerous to
fall into a kind of score keeping

00:41:19.310 --> 00:41:21.990
of hours, of who has
more time to work.

00:41:21.990 --> 00:41:24.500
But just to kind of -- you
know we're all trying to get

00:41:24.500 --> 00:41:27.260
to the same place, which
is to finish our books.

00:41:27.260 --> 00:41:28.560
So --

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:29.860
&gt;&gt; Well, thank you
both very, very much.

00:41:29.860 --> 00:41:31.160
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:41:31.160 --> 00:41:32.460
[applause]

00:41:32.460 --> 00:41:34.260
&gt;&gt; And thank you!

